{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474900"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:26:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:26:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12451"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12451"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.37,0.43,0.07,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4959"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110683"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4959"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12451"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92931"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1945"},{"type":"tags","id":"2067"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"9339"},{"type":"tags","id":"9687"},{"type":"tags","id":"9690"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8140"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8253"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9674"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10336"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10343"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11565"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14582"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41820"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110683"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 2-month-old child presents to the outpatient department for a follow-up appointment. One month earlier, he was brought to the emergency department with concerns of respiratory distress, expiratory stridor exacerbated by a respiratory infection, and feeding difficulties. A barium swallow was performed revealing normal oesophageal motility and no evidence of tracheo-oesophageal fistula or external compression. He was managed conservatively with humidified air, careful feedings, and antibiotics for infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn his history, he was born prematurely at 34 weeks and was admitted to the neonatal intensive care unit for 10 days for respiratory distress syndrome, where he was treated with surfactant therapy and was discharged home in good health.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring this appointment, his parents are still concerned regarding his ongoing biphasic stridor, which has only shown minimal improvement since his previous admission to the hospital, as well as ongoing feeding difficulties and poor weight gain. On physical examination, an expiratory stridor is heard, with a mild increase in work of breathing. His oxygen saturation is 98% on room air.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the next most appropriate investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary function tests","Flexible bronchoscopy","Rigid laryngotracheobronchoscopy","CT scan","MRI scan"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is most likely consistent with tracheomalacia, which is a condition where the trachea is floppy or collapsible, leading to partial or complete obstruction of the airway. This is consistent with the clinical findings which include the presence of expiratory stridor and difficulty breathing while feeding. A lower tracheal narrowing may also be seen on barium swallow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations for tracheomalacia initially include minimally invasive investigations such as an airway screen and barium swallow. The gold standard evaluation of malacia (laryngomalacia, tracheomalacia or bronchomalacia) is via direct visualisation, however, methods may differ and there are advantages and disadvantages for each.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERigid laryngotracheobronchoscopy (LTB)\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexible bronchoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E are two procedures that can be undertaken to assess tracheomalacia. They both require general anaesthesia and whilst the latter is less invasive than rigid LTB, flexible bronchoscopy does not provide the same level of detail or ability to manipulate the airway, which is essential for a definitive diagnosis of tracheomalacia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERigid bronchoscopy can be used to assess for laryngo-, tracheo-, and broncho-malacia as well as vocal cord palsy, subglottic stenosis, and webbing, amongst many other conditions. Rigid LTB provides superior visualisation and allows for better manipulation of the airway, which is crucial for diagnosing tracheomalacia. It is also better when assessing the severity of airway collapse. Flexible bronchoscopy, when compared to LTB, may not offer the same visualisation (i.e. image quality is not always as good) and airway manipulation (i.e. cannot exclude some anatomical defects such as laryngeal cleft). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary function tests (PFTs)\u003C/strong\u003E are non-invasive tests that measure lung function and detect any restriction in airflow. These tests can measure the amount of air that can be inhaled and exhaled, the speed of airflow, and the amount of oxygen in the blood. PFTs measure lung function but do not provide direct visualisation of the airway. Furthermore, spirometry cannot be reliably performed until 5 years old, while lung clearance index and multiple breath washout tests cannot be tested before 3 years old. Therefore LTB would likely be the primary diagnostic tool in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT (computed tomography)\u003C/strong\u003E scan is an imaging test that uses x-rays to create detailed cross-sectional images of the body. CT scans are used to diagnose a wide range of conditions and injuries, including lung conditions such as lung cancer, pneumonia, and bronchitis. It can detect structural changes in the lung, airways and blood vessels, and help identify the cause of the symptoms. However, a CT scan often requires a general anaesthetic (although a \u0027feed and wrap\u0027 could be attempted). This is often also required if a \u0027breath hold\u0027 or inspiratory/expiratory films are required. However, for tracheomalacia, the gold standard evaluation would be through an LTB.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI (magnetic resonance imaging)\u003C/strong\u003E is another imaging test that uses a magnetic field, radio waves, and a computer to create detailed images of the body. MRI can be used to visualise the lung, airways and blood vessels in great detail, and help identify the cause of the symptoms. It is more sensitive than a CT scan but is not a great modality for visualising air-filled organs like the lung (without special modifications to the testing protocols/techniques). It would also require a general anaesthetic for a young child to keep still, and therefore direct visualisation with LTB is still the preferred method of visualisation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The gold standard investigation for tracheomalacia is through direct visualisation of the airway with a rigid laryngotracheobronchoscopy."],"references":["Yang D, Cascella M. Tracheomalacia. [Updated 2022 Jul 9]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.","Hysinger EB, Hart CK, Burg G, et al. Differences in Flexible and Rigid Bronchoscopy for Assessment of Tracheomalacia. Laryngoscope 2021; 131:201\u2013204."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92931"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12451"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92931"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-03T08:00:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-03T08:00:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4959"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110683"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemC